{"id": 68954, "date": "1972-02-04T11:08:03", "date_gmt": "1972-02-04T19:08:03", "guid": {"rendered": "https://estreetshuffle.com/?p=68954"}, "modified": "2026-05-11T19:07:16", "modified_gmt": "2026-05-12T02:07:16", "slug": "come-on-billy-break-out-the-wine", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/02/04/come-on-billy-break-out-the-wine/", "title": {"rendered": "Come On Billy, Break Out the Wine"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>Some songs from the Bruce Springsteen Band era feel less like a snapshot and more like a signpost.</p>\n<p>This one is both.</p>\n<p>Written in early 1971 and performed at least four times that summer, &#8220;Come On Billy, Break Out the Wine&#8221; is both a wonderfully captured recording of the full Bruce Springsteen Band (including horn section and backup singers) at their brassy best and also a fascinating sneak peak at themes and tropes Springsteen would explore over the next few years.</p>\n<div class=\"jetpack-video-wrapper\"><span class=\"embed-youtube\" style=\"text-align:center; display: block;\"><iframe loading=\"lazy\" class=\"youtube-player\" width=\"758\" height=\"427\" src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/xfWi8p5wbIk?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;fs=1&#038;hl=en-US&#038;autohide=2&#038;wmode=transparent\" allowfullscreen=\"true\" style=\"border:0;\" sandbox=\"allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-popups allow-presentation allow-popups-to-escape-sandbox\"></iframe></span></div>\n<p>Sometimes referred to on bootlegs as &#8220;Nothing Can Stop Me Now,&#8221; &#8220;Come On Billy, Break Out the Wine&#8221; features a narrator desperate to escape his one-horse town with his friend Billy.</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>Come on Billy,\u00a0 won&#8217;t you break out the wine</em><br />\n<em>I wanna see you pop that cork</em><br />\n<em>Today&#8217;s the day that we&#8217;ve all been waiting for</em><br />\n<em>Now I&#8217;m gonna get down to some serious celebrating,</em><br />\n<em>We ain&#8217;t been out of this one horse town</em><br />\n<em>Since I was dropped off by the stork</em></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>Nothing can stop me now\u00a0</em><br />\n<em>Got my ticket to New York\u00a0</em><br />\n<em>Oh nothing can stop me boy</em><br />\n<em>No no nothing can stop me now\u00a0</em></p>\n<p>It&#8217;s never made clear what the celebration&#8217;s about\u2013graduation, perhaps? Or maybe it&#8217;s simply the purchase of a bus ticket that transforms our hero from dreamer to traveler.</p>\n<p>Regardless, he and Billy are eager to blow out of town. For our narrator, at least, it&#8217;ll be the first time he&#8217;s ever left.</p>\n<p>Bruce&#8217;s vocals are wild, almost manic, and the whole song barrels like a bus toward the big city. What passes as a chorus is a one-line mantra&#8211;<em>nothing can stop me now\u2013</em>that gains power with every utterance.</p>\n<p>Before we even reach the second verse, we feel the narrator&#8217;s desperate need for escape, his small-town claustrophobia, and his utter conviction that his destiny is just a bus ride away\u2013themes that hadn&#8217;t yet but soon will come to characterize Springsteen&#8217;s work.</p>\n<p>But the signposts are about to get even clearer:</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>Yeah I&#8217;ll say my goodbyes to Mary</em><br />\n<em>She&#8217;s a standing there at the door</em><br />\n<em>I don&#8217;t wanna leave that women so bluesy</em><br />\n<em>I never left that girl before, oh no no</em><br />\n<em>A man&#8217;s gotta seek his fortune</em><br />\n<em>And a man gotta seek his fame</em></p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>I tell you when I get back</em><br />\n<em>This whole town&#8217;s gonna know my name\u00a0</em><br />\n<em>No nothing can stop me boy\u00a0</em><br />\n<em>Not even my mama\u00a0</em><br />\n<em>Oh no nothing can stop me now\u00a0</em></p>\n<p>Before he pulls out of town to win, our hero needs to say goodbye to his girl Mary, who&#8217;s standing at the door. (It must be a screen door.)</p>\n<p>It&#8217;s a first glimpse at a song that wouldn&#8217;t even begin to take shape for years, although reportedly there&#8217;s a 1972 song (which I&#8217;ve never heard) called &#8220;Angelina&#8221; that shares the first two lines of &#8220;Thunder Road.&#8221; If so, we can probably trace its ancestry back even further to &#8220;Come On Billy.&#8221;</p>\n<p>There&#8217;s a delightful David Sancious solo at this point\u2013always a highlight of any BSB song\u2013and then we get yet one more glimpse into the future.</p>\n<p style=\"padding-left: 40px;\"><em>Hey Mr. Greyhound driver</em><br />\n<em>It&#8217;s good to see you right on time</em><br />\n<em>All I wanna know is how far do we go\u00a0</em><br />\n<em>What time do we arrive\u00a0</em><br />\n<em>No no nothing can stop me now</em></p>\n<p>Well hey there, bus driver. Don&#8217;t forget to name your kids.</p>\n<p>Without the benefit of hindsight, we might dismiss &#8220;Come On Billy, Break Out the Wine&#8221; as a short-lived trifle in an evolving artist&#8217;s repertoire\u2013because it certainly was.</p>\n<p>But it&#8217;s also a fun and fascinating peek into how beloved songs sometimes start from humble beginnings.</p>\n<p><img data-recalc-dims=\"1\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" data-attachment-id=\"68955\" data-permalink=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/02/04/come-on-billy-break-out-the-wine/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_1/#main\" data-orig-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_1.jpg?fit=1024%2C1400&amp;ssl=1\" data-orig-size=\"1024,1400\" data-comments-opened=\"0\" data-image-meta=\"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}\" data-image-title=\"lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_1\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-large-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_1.jpg?fit=749%2C1024&amp;ssl=1\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-68955\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_1.jpg?resize=758%2C1036&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" width=\"758\" height=\"1036\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_1.jpg?w=1024&amp;ssl=1 1024w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_1.jpg?resize=219%2C300&amp;ssl=1 219w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_1.jpg?resize=749%2C1024&amp;ssl=1 749w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_1.jpg?resize=768%2C1050&amp;ssl=1 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 758px) 100vw, 758px\" /> <img data-recalc-dims=\"1\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" data-attachment-id=\"68956\" data-permalink=\"https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1972/02/04/come-on-billy-break-out-the-wine/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_2/#main\" data-orig-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_2.jpg?fit=1020%2C1395&amp;ssl=1\" data-orig-size=\"1020,1395\" data-comments-opened=\"0\" data-image-meta=\"{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}\" data-image-title=\"lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_2\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-large-file=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_2.jpg?fit=749%2C1024&amp;ssl=1\" class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-68956\" src=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_2.jpg?resize=758%2C1037&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" width=\"758\" height=\"1037\" srcset=\"https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_2.jpg?w=1020&amp;ssl=1 1020w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_2.jpg?resize=219%2C300&amp;ssl=1 219w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_2.jpg?resize=749%2C1024&amp;ssl=1 749w, https://i0.wp.com/estreetshuffle.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/lyricsheet_nothingcanstopme_2.jpg?resize=768%2C1050&amp;ssl=1 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 758px) 100vw, 758px\" /></p>\n<p><strong>Come On Billy, Break Out the Wine<br />\nNever recorded</strong><br />\n<strong>Never released</strong><br />\n<strong>First performed:</strong> July 10, 1971 (Lincroft, NJ)<br />\n<strong>Last performed:</strong> July 29, 1971 (South Amboy, NJ)</p>\n<p>\u00a9 May 11, 2026</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>Some songs from the Bruce Springsteen Band era feel less like a snapshot and more like a signpost. This one is both. Written in early&hellip;</p>\n", "protected": false}, "author": 1, "featured_media": 0, "comment_status": "closed", "ping_status": "closed", "sticky": false, "template": "", "format": "standard", "meta": {"_monsterinsights_skip_tracking": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_active": false, "_monsterinsights_sitenote_note": "", "_monsterinsights_sitenote_category": 0, "_jetpack_newsletter_access": "", "_jetpack_dont_email_post_to_subs": false,